          <p>The validator will:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Check that all required fields are present</li>
            <li>Verify data types and formats</li>
            <li>Validate schema references</li>
            <li>Show detailed error messages if something is wrong</li>
          </ul>
        </section>
        
        <section class="about-section">
          <h2>Creating Your Potion</h2>
          <p>Each potion consists of <strong>two files</strong>:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>JSON file</strong> - Machine-readable format for AI agents (required)</li>
            <li><strong>Markdown file</strong> - Human-readable web version (required)</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h3>Step 1: Choose the Right Category</h3>
          <p>Determine which category your potion belongs to:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Layouts</strong> - Full-page structures (dashboards, landing pages, app shells)</li>
            <li><strong>Components</strong> - Reusable UI elements (buttons, dialogs, navbars, forms)</li>
            <li><strong>Features</strong> - Complete user flows (auth, onboarding, checkout)</li>
            <li><strong>Patterns</strong> - Design patterns and guidelines</li>
            <li><strong>Tooling</strong> - Developer tools and integrations</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h3>Step 2: Create the JSON File</h3>
          <p>Create a new JSON file in the appropriate directory:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><code>src/statics/potions/layouts/your-potion-name.json</code></li>
            <li><code>src/statics/potions/components/your-potion-name.json</code></li>
            <li><code>src/statics/potions/features/your-potion-name.json</code></li>
            <li><code>src/statics/potions/patterns/your-potion-name.json</code></li>
            <li><code>src/statics/potions/tooling/your-potion-name.json</code></li>
          </ul>
          
          <h3>Step 3: Create the Markdown (Web) File</h3>
          <p>Create a corresponding Markdown file in the potions directory. This is the human-readable web version that appears on the website:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><code>src/potions/layouts/your-potion-name.md</code></li>
            <li><code>src/potions/components/your-potion-name.md</code></li>
            <li><code>src/potions/features/your-potion-name.md</code></li>
            <li><code>src/potions/patterns/your-potion-name.md</code></li>
            <li><code>src/potions/tooling/your-potion-name.md</code></li>
          </ul>
          
          <p><strong>Important:</strong> The Markdown file must include an <code>agentManifest</code> field in the front matter that links to your JSON file. This creates the connection between the web version and the AI-readable version.</p>
          
          <div class="example-box">
            <p><strong>Example Markdown front matter:</strong></p>
            <pre><code>---
layout: 'potion'
title: 'Your Component Name'
publicationDate: '2026-01-15'
excerpt: 'Brief description of your component (1-2 sentences)'
category: 'Components'
tags:
  - tag1
  - tag2
  - tag3
agentManifest: 'potions/components/your-potion-name.json'
---

# Your Component Name

[Your detailed markdown content here...]</code></pre>
          </div>
          
          <p><strong>Creating the Markdown file:</strong></p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>With AI:</strong> You can use AI to generate the Markdown file based on your JSON. Provide the JSON to your AI assistant and ask it to create a comprehensive, human-readable Markdown version with detailed specifications.</li>
            <li><strong>Manually:</strong> You can also write it by hand. Review existing potions (like <code>navbar.md</code> or <code>dashboard.md</code>) to see the format and level of detail expected.</li>
          </ul>
          
          <p>The Markdown file should include:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Overview and description</li>
            <li>Component/layout structure and hierarchy</li>
            <li>Detailed specifications (dimensions, states, behavior)</li>
            <li>Responsive design breakpoints</li>
            <li>Accessibility requirements</li>
            <li>Animation specifications</li>
            <li>Framework patterns (framework-agnostic descriptions)</li>
            <li>Testing checklist</li>
          </ul>
          
          <p><strong>Review existing examples:</strong> Check out existing potions to understand the format:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><code>src/potions/components/navbar.md</code></li>
            <li><code>src/potions/components/dialog.md</code></li>
            <li><code>src/potions/layouts/dashboard.md</code></li>
          </ul>
          
          <h3>Step 4: Follow the Schema</h3>
          <p>Use the appropriate category schema as your guide. Key things to include:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>All required fields from the base schema (id, version, name, category, tags, description, etc.)</li>
            <li>Category-specific required fields (e.g., componentSpec for components, layoutModel for layouts)</li>
            <li>Comprehensive AI agent instructions</li>
            <li>Framework patterns (React, Vue, Angular, Svelte)</li>
            <li>Styling approaches (Tailwind, CSS Modules, etc.)</li>
            <li>Accessibility requirements</li>
            <li>Testing checklist</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h3>Step 5: Validate</h3>
          <p>Use the <a href="{{relativePath 'validator.html'}}">Schema Validator</a> to ensure your JSON is correct before submitting. Make sure both your JSON and Markdown files are properly formatted and the <code>agentManifest</code> path in the Markdown file correctly points to your JSON file.</p>
        </section>
        
        <section class="about-section">
          <h2>Pull Request Process</h2>
          
          <h3>Before Submitting</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>✅ Validate your potion JSON using the validator</li>
            <li>✅ Ensure all required fields are present in JSON</li>
            <li>✅ Check that your potion follows the schema structure</li>
            <li>✅ Test that the JSON is valid (no syntax errors)</li>
            <li>✅ Create the Markdown file with proper front matter</li>
            <li>✅ Verify the <code>agentManifest</code> path in Markdown points to your JSON file</li>
            <li>✅ Review existing Markdown files to match the format and detail level</li>
            <li>✅ Use a descriptive commit message</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h3>Pull Request Template</h3>
          <p>When creating your PR, include:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Category</strong> - Which category does this potion belong to?</li>
            <li><strong>Description</strong> - What does this potion provide?</li>
            <li><strong>Validation</strong> - Confirmation that it passes schema validation</li>
            <li><strong>Example use case</strong> - When would someone use this potion?</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h3>What Happens Next</h3>
          <ol>
            <li>We'll review your potion for schema compliance</li>
            <li>We'll check that it follows best practices</li>
            <li>We may suggest improvements or ask questions</li>
            <li>Once approved, your potion will be merged and published!</li>
          </ol>
        </section>
        
        <section class="about-section">
          <h2>Best Practices</h2>
          
          <h3>Writing AI Agent Instructions</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Be specific about styling enforcement (e.g., "MUST use Tailwind if detected")</li>
            <li>Include detection steps for framework and styling system</li>
            <li>Provide clear implementation steps</li>
            <li>Include output constraints (what to avoid)</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h3>Framework Patterns</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Provide examples for React, Vue, Angular, and Svelte when possible</li>
            <li>Use framework-agnostic descriptions when patterns are similar</li>
            <li>Include state management patterns (useState, refs, etc.)</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h3>Accessibility</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Always specify WCAG compliance level (A, AA, or AAA)</li>
            <li>Include keyboard navigation requirements</li>
            <li>Document ARIA attributes needed</li>
            <li>Provide screen reader considerations</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h3>Testing</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Include a comprehensive testing checklist</li>
            <li>Cover functional, accessibility, and responsive testing</li>
            <li>Include edge cases and error states</li>
          </ul>
        </section>
        
